A reply to Stephanie:<br><br>
All war is horrible. It is the exquisite essence of inhumanity. It is the expression of self preservation, a survival drive at the level of species genetic memory.<br><br>
Through the ages, these experiences are born by the Warrior, a class of individuals who bear the burden of horror on behalf of the people they protect.<br><br>
The Warrior is &quot;compensated&quot; for this burden with care, compassion, and priveleges given by those who are protected. <br><br>
It is really a very simple formula. The American People ignored this formula with the Warriors of the Vietnam War.<br><br>
My personal experience can be very briefly summarized:<br><br>
I joined the Army and participated in the Vietnam War because it was my duty to my country. I am and always will be proudly an American. I felt it was a crime to disobey the wishes of my country. I did not want the shame of seeing my picture hung in the Post Office with common criminals.<br><br>
I fought in the Vietnam War to the best of my ability. I received decorations. I saved fellow Warriors. I fought the enemy. I killed the enemy. The enemy tried to kill me. I survived. I was and continue to be proud of that accomplishment. <br><br>
I was returned home from the jungle and raw combat in a 48 hour period. I was spat upon. I was denied food at a restaurant because I was in uniform. No one showed any interest in what I had to say. No one wanted to hear anything. I was even told once that it was me they wished had perished in battle.<br><br>
This discrimination continued. I stuffed it all. I stuffed much of my self at the same time. It was a forced denial.<br><br>
The country then, after a while, pardoned all those who had criminally fled to avoid fighting in the Vietnam War. All Vietnam War Veterans and their combat struggles and pain became totally invalidated. Those who died in combat were dishonored and their memories tarnished.  <br><br>
We had done our duty for absolutely nothing! Our fellow Warriors who perished did so for absolutely no reason. The dead remained unburied. Many of us became &quot;dead&quot; as well.<br>
Those who we were sworn to protect honored those who committed crimes to run away from their obligations to their country.<br><br>
I bear no ill will to those who cut and ran. I feel only pity. They have a burden of shame with which to deal.<br><br>
It was and continues to be a double bind with which most of us live in pain. Post Traumatic Stress Disorder is a very real thing.<br><br>
I have never had a &quot;homecoming&quot; from the Vietnam War. It lives in my mind all the time. I remain locked in combat.<br><br>
I have much more to say, but at a later time. There is only so much I can discuss befor I begin to react adversely.<br><br>
I appreciate your open minded quest for information and this opportunity to speak with those who are truly interested. 
